\fs26 \cf2 \cb9 Agreed on all points. The build order is correct.\
\
Two implementation details worth flagging before you write the spec:\
\
**Arc role distribution needs a default by book size.** The four arc roles (introduce / deepen / challenge / resolve) will naturally cluster wrong without a distribution rule. A 5-chapter book should probably run 1-2-1-1. A 12-chapter book might run 2-4-3-3. If the planner doesn't have a target distribution, the novelty scorer alone won't catch a book that's all 
\f2 deepen
\f0  with no 
\f2 challenge
\f0 . Build the distribution table into the book-level config alongside the exercise quotas.\
\
**Steps 3 and 4 need a specific execution order.** The quota validator should run first and eliminate invalid configurations before the novelty scorer sees them. If novelty scoring runs on a candidate set that still includes quota violations, you get a valid-scoring but invalid-quota chapter sequence that passes. The planner pipeline should be: generate candidates \uc0\u8594  quota filter \u8594  novelty score \u8594  select. Not score then filter.\
\
One more that fell out of the discussion: archetypes should carry **transition compatibility** rules. Some sequences break narrative logic regardless of weight settings \'97 two 
\f2 challenge
\f0  chapters back-to-back without a 
\f2 deepen
\f0  between them reads as relentless rather than building. A simple allowed-following-archetype list per archetype type catches this cheaply, before you need the full novelty scorer.\
\
After those three are locked in, the reorder mode in step 5 becomes much safer because the archetype + transition rules already constrain what the reorder is operating inside.\
\
The core architecture is right. These are implementation guards, not structural changes.\
